5.04.01 - Product Flow and Segregation Controls

Requirement Description:

Primus GFS requires facilities to maintain proper product flow to prevent cross-contamination. Product handling areas must be designed and operated to ensure separation between raw and finished products, with clear segregation protocols in place.

Implementation Procedure:

The facility maintains strict product flow controls through physical barriers and operational procedures. Production areas are divided into zones (raw material, processing, and finished product) with designated pathways marked by yellow floor lines. Staff must follow one-way traffic patterns and use separate equipment for raw and finished product areas. Required materials include zone signage, color-coded equipment, and physical barriers where needed.

The Production Supervisor conducts flow pattern monitoring every 2 hours during operational shifts. Inspections occur facility-wide with focus on transition points between zones. The supervisor spends approximately 15 minutes per inspection round, documenting observations and any corrective actions needed. Additional checks occur during shift changes and when production lines are modified.

All observations are recorded on Form OPS-101 (Product Flow Monitoring Log). Required data points include: time of inspection, zones checked, employee compliance with flow patterns, equipment placement verification, and any violations observed. Records are maintained in the QA office for 2 years and reviewed weekly by the QA Manager.

Monitoring criteria includes: 100% compliance with designated flow patterns, zero instances of cross-zone equipment usage, and proper maintenance of physical barriers. Verification occurs through direct observation, review of security camera footage, and monthly facility flow audits. Any deviation requires immediate correction and documentation.

Corrective Actions:

- Immediate stop of affected operations if cross-contamination risk identified

- Incident documentation on Form CAPA-101

- Root cause analysis within 24 hours

- Staff retraining as needed

- Follow-up audit within 48 hours

5.04.02 - Hand Washing Facilities and Procedures

Requirement Description:

Adequate hand washing facilities must be provided and properly maintained. Facilities must be easily accessible with appropriate supplies and clear instructions for proper hand washing procedures.

Implementation Procedure:

Hand washing stations are equipped with hot and cold running water, liquid soap dispensers, paper towels, and hands-free waste containers. Each station displays bilingual hand washing instructions with pictorials. Required supplies include: antibacterial soap, paper towels, sanitizer (minimum 60% alcohol), and maintenance supplies. Stations include hands-free faucets and foot-operated doors where possible.

The Sanitation Lead inspects all hand washing stations three times daily (pre-shift, mid-shift, and end-of-shift) at all facility entry points and within production areas. Each inspection takes approximately 10 minutes per station. Temperature checks of water supply must be conducted (minimum 100°F required), and supply levels monitored.

Documentation occurs on Form SAN-102 (Hand Wash Station Monitoring Log). Required recording includes: inspection time, water temperature, supply levels, cleanliness status, and any maintenance needs. Records are maintained electronically in the Sanitation Department database and reviewed daily by the Sanitation Manager.

Acceptance criteria includes: water temperature 100-120°F, fully stocked supplies, functional equipment, and clean/sanitary conditions. Verification through visual inspection, temperature monitoring, and weekly ATP testing of surfaces. Compliance must be ≥98% at all times.

Corrective Actions:

- Immediate restocking of supplies if depleted

- Equipment repair within 2 hours if malfunction detected

- Documentation on Form CAPA-102

- Investigation of repeated issues

- Weekly verification of corrective actions

