5.04.10 - Protection of Exposed Product During Storage and Transportation

Requirement Description:

All exposed product must be protected during storage and transportation to prevent contamination. Products must be covered, protected from condensation, and stored off the floor to prevent contact with moisture or contaminants.

Implementation Procedure:

Step-by-step procedures include inspecting all storage areas daily for proper product protection, ensuring products are covered with food-grade materials, maintaining proper storage heights (minimum 6 inches off floor), and verifying protection from overhead condensation. Required materials include plastic pallet covers, food-grade tarps, dunnage, pallets, and moisture-resistant coverings.

The Warehouse Supervisor conducts inspections twice daily (6:00 AM and 2:00 PM) in all storage areas and loading docks. Additional checks occur during product movement or staging. Each inspection should take approximately 15 minutes per area. The supervisor must verify proper coverage, height requirements, and absence of condensation risks.

Documentation is recorded on Form WH-201 (Product Protection Checklist). Records must include date, time, inspector name, areas checked, conditions observed, and any corrective actions taken. Forms are maintained in the QA office for minimum 2 years. The QA Manager reviews records weekly and conducts monthly verification audits.

Monitoring criteria includes: 100% product coverage when required, minimum 6-inch floor clearance, zero evidence of water/condensation contact, intact protective materials. Visual inspections verify compliance. Temperature and humidity monitoring in storage areas ensures conditions don't promote condensation.

Corrective Actions:

- Immediately cover exposed product

- Move product to compliant storage location

- Inspect product for damage/contamination

- Document incident on Form CAPA-110

- Investigate root cause

- Retrain staff if procedural gaps identified

- Follow-up inspection within 24 hours

5.04.11 - Cleaning Equipment Storage

Requirement Description:

All cleaning equipment must be stored in designated areas separate from production and storage areas. Equipment must be organized, maintained clean, and stored in a manner that prevents contamination.

Implementation Procedure:

Cleaning equipment storage requires dedicated rooms or areas with proper ventilation, drainage, and organization systems. Equipment includes color-coded tools, cleaning chemicals, brushes, mops, buckets, and PPE. Storage areas must have appropriate shelving, hooks, and containment systems. All items must be labeled and stored off the floor.

The Sanitation Supervisor inspects storage areas daily at start of shift (5:00 AM) and end of shift (6:00 PM). Weekly deep cleaning occurs every Sunday. Storage areas are locked with restricted access. Each inspection includes checking organization, cleanliness, proper storage, and inventory of supplies.

Form SAN-301 (Cleaning Equipment Storage Log) documents daily inspections. Required information includes equipment condition, chemical inventory, storage compliance, cleanliness rating, and inspector verification. Records maintained in Sanitation office for 2 years. Monthly audits by QA Manager verify compliance.

Storage requirements include: All equipment clean and dry before storage, chemicals in secondary containment, proper separation of tools by zone/area, no signs of pest activity, proper ventilation maintained. Weekly ATP testing of cleaned equipment, monthly environmental monitoring of storage areas.

Corrective Actions:

- Remove/clean any soiled equipment

- Reorganize storage area

- Document non-compliance on Form CAPA-111

- Review sanitation procedures

- Conduct staff retraining

- Follow-up inspection required within 12 hours

